SUMMARIZER="A">

Hurricane Hugo struck South Carolina Thursday after thousands of coastal residents 
were evacuated inland. By late afternoon the storm was upgraded to category 4. 
Hurricane-force winds first hit the coast at 9:15 p.m. and by midnight 119 mph winds 
were reported in Charleston and up to 135 mph as the eye passed nearby. Hugo was 
expected to turn north and cause severe flooding as it passed up the coast. As of 
Thursday evening about 12,000 people had checked into 83 shelters across South 
Carolina. A spokesman for the Red Cross said that tens of thousands of people were in 
shelters along the Eastern seaboard.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d097"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890922-0119"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="A">

As Hurricane Hugo's 135 mph wind roared outside, Charleston S.C.'s mayor Joseph P. 
Riley, city officials and a few reporters stayed in Charleston's City Hall watching the 
storm's fury. The building's tin roof ripped off and water seeped down into the City 
Council chamber. Phone and electric service to the city command post was knocked 
out. When the eye of the storm passed, Riley took reporters out of the 188-year-old 
building to look at the damage. The tin roof was in the gutter, slate tiles were scattered 
on the ground. Bricks, sticks and leaves littered the street. "It's scarcely a late summer 
breeze," he commented.</SUM>

