SUMMARIZER="A">

Hurricane Hugo did not simply wreak devastation on the Carolinas; it brought about 
repayment of a long overdue debt. Kingston, N.Y., the capital of New York in 1777, was 
burned by the British in October of that year. New York Gov. George Clinton received 
from South Carolina Gov. Abraham Livingston a letter dated March 31, 1778 enclosing 
1,000 New York pounds  "...for the charitable purpose of alleviating the distresses of the 
now-indigent inhabitants of the town of Kingston...". A local historian remembered the 
letter and now Kingston is raising money to help Charleston, S.C. recover from the 
ravages of Hugo.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d097"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890922-0049"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="A">

Hurricane Hugo has put to test the city of Charleston, S.C. which has survived 
earthquake, battle and storm in its 300-year history. The storm with winds reaching 135 
mph hit Charleston head-on Thursday night, the first major hurricane to strike 
Charleston since Hurricane Gracie made landfall 70 miles to the south in 1959. 
Charleston has survived a tornado that killed 32 people, injured hundreds and caused 
$2 million in property damage in 1938, shot and shell of two wars, any number of 
smaller hurricanes, and the earthquake of Aug. 31, 1886 that measured 7.7 on the 
Richter scale, killed 110, and destroyed 102 buildings.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d097"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890925-0054"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="A">

Local authorities credit residents who showed respect for hurricane warnings for the low 
casualty rate from Hurricane Hugo. Charleston S.C. bore the brunt of Hugo's fury, but 
only two of the state's 17 deaths were in the Charleston area. A local Red Cross official 
estimated that 18,000 residents of Charleston and surrounding counties headed for 
shelters and tens of thousands  motored inland. Charleston Mayor Riley said that those 
in shelters and those who evacuated inland "...were potential victims of injury and 
death." North Charleston Mayor Bourne credited people for heeding the warnings, 
saying "It was bad, but it could have been a lot worse."</SUM>

<SUM
