SUMMARIZER="A">

The two biggest home and auto insurers in the Carolinas estimated Tuesday that 
claims from Hurricane Hugo will reach $600 million, making it the most expensive ever. 
State Farm expects claims of $500 million and Nationwide estimates $100 million. 
Damage from Hugo was particularly high since it hit Charleston directly and then veered 
northwest hitting other population centers rather than heading out to sea. Overall 
damage to insured property will far exceed the record $752.5 million from Hurricane 
Frederic in 1979. Overall 1989 catastrophic losses for the industry now total about $1.6 
billion and Hugo will probably make this year the costliest to date.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d097"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ890928-0084"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="A">

Damage from Hurricane Hugo which hit the Carolinas and Caribbean last week will 
reduce third-quarter earnings for several insurers. American International Group expect 
a reduction in pretax earnings of $35-45 million with reinsurance covering most 
damages above $35 million. St. Paul estimates the pretax cost of Hugo as less than 
$50 million after its reinsurance contracts are figured in and Cigna is estimated to have 
a 35-45% reduction in after-tax per share earnings. State Farm expects its total claims 
for Hugo to reach $500 million which is more than three times the record $165 million 
for Hurricane Alicia in 1983.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d097"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ890927-0018"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="A">

Losses to insurers from Hurricane Hugo far surpass the $752.5 million for Hurricane 
Frederick in 1979, but analysts and company officials predict no increase in premium 
rates before mid-1990. Mr. Ruoff of Fred S. James figures that even if losses reach $5 
billion insurers won't feel enough "financial pain" to make them boost premium rates 
right away. In the last three years hurricane and storm seasons have been rather mild 
so insurers haven't had to dip into reserves. Most insurers also protect themselves by 
buying reinsurance, and even State Farm, which doesn't buy reinsurance, believes its 
reserves are large enough to absorb its losses.</SUM>
